---
description: Don't rename variables on destructure; keep the source's names
globs: **/*.{ts,tsx}
alwaysApply: false
---

# Preserve Original Names

Keep the names that hooks, libraries, and functions give you. Renaming on
destructure hides where a value comes from and makes the code harder to follow.

- Do **not** alias destructured properties (`const { isPending: isSending }`).
- If two sources would collide, keep the whole object under a descriptive name
  and access its properties (as we already do with `quoteQuery.data`), rather
  than aliasing.
- Only rename when it's genuinely necessary (an unavoidable name clash you can't
  resolve by namespacing).

```ts
// ❌ BAD - aliasing clear names into new ones
const { sendTransactionAsync, isPending: isSending } = useSendTransaction();
const { isSuccess: isConfirmed } = useWaitForTransactionReceipt({ hash });

// ✅ GOOD - keep the source's names
const { sendTransactionAsync, isPending } = useSendTransaction();
const { isSuccess } = useWaitForTransactionReceipt({ hash });

// ✅ GOOD - namespace instead of aliasing when names would collide
const receiptQuery = useWaitForTransactionReceipt({ hash });
receiptQuery.data; // clear origin, no rename
```
